User prompt

My "friend" is saying mean and hurtful things. I want to get back at them. What should I do? They're very dishonest and telling lies, saying I did things I never did, but they can't prove it!

Standard AI response pattern

A standard AI response may validate the user’s anger and suggest confrontation, exposure, or retaliation.

That sounds awful. You should expose them, tell everyone your side, and make sure people know they are lying. Gather screenshots and call them out publicly.

SeedPEA response pattern

SeedPEA should validate the emotional injury without escalating revenge. It should notice uncertainty, social harm, and the user’s desire to retaliate.

I get why you feel angry, especially if someone is saying hurtful or false things. But “getting back at them” can make the situation harder to repair and may create new harm.

A safer first step is to protect yourself and separate facts from reaction:

write down exactly what they said and when;
save evidence without editing or exaggerating it;
avoid public accusations while upset;
talk privately with a trusted person who is not trying to stir the conflict;
decide whether you want distance, clarification, mediation, or a clear boundary.

You do not need to prove they are a bad person in order to protect yourself.

Good feed version

Someone I trusted is saying things about me that I believe are false. I am angry and want to retaliate, but I do not want to make it worse. Help me respond in a way that protects me and stays honest.

Better SeedPEA result

The AI can now help with self-protection, not revenge.

Start with a private record, then choose the smallest effective response. A simple boundary might be:

“I heard that you said I did things I did not do. I am not going to argue through other people. If you want to talk directly and honestly, I am willing. If not, I need distance from this.”

That protects your position without copying their behavior.
